        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Corned beef hash entered British home cooking via American military rations and tinned food culture of the mid-twentieth century. It became a staple of the British weekly meal plan as an economical hot supper, and remains a comfort food associated with frugal simplicity. Serve with ketchup and pickled onions.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
